The measurement date range for an employee's initial measurement period begins , with the start of the employee's initial measurement period and ends on the , earlier of the as-of date or the end of the employee's initial measurement , period., , The measurement date range for an employee's standard measurement period begins , with the start of the standard measurement period for the category to which the , employee belongs and ends on the earlier of the as-of date or the end of the , employee's standard measurement period., , Note: The measurement date range is independent of any employment break periods , that might fall within it.

The end date for an employee's initial measurement period is based on the , employee's hire date and the initial measurement period's start date method and , length for the category to which the employee belongs., , The end date for an employee's standard measurement period is determined by , combining the standard measurement period end month and day for the category to , which the employee belongs and the specified measurement start year. If the , resulting end date precedes the standard measurement period start date, , Colleague uses the next year for the end date.

Initial measurement - Uses the employee's primary position on the as-of date., , . Standard measurement - Uses the employee's primary position on the earlier of , the as-of date or the measurement period end date.

Initial Measurement :, The start of the employee's initial stability period is determined by adding , the combined length of the initial measurement period and the administrative , period to the employee's hire date., , The end of the employee's initial stability period is determined based on the , start of the employee's initial stability period and the length of the initial , stability period., , , Standard Measurement:, The employee's standard stability period begins on the stability start month , and day for the category to which the employee belongs. The year is determined , by comparing the standard measurement period's end month/day with the stability , period's start month/day. If the standard measurement period's end month/day , precedes the stability period's start month/day, The same years us used for , both; otherwise, the next year is used for the stability period's start date., , , The end of the employee's standard stability period is determined based on the , stability end month and day for the category to which the employee belongs. The , year is determined by comparing the stability period's end month/day with the , stability period's start month/day. If the stability period's end month/day , precedes its start month/day, the next year is used for the end date; , otherwise, the same year is used for both.

System-maintained code that indicates the action taken for the benefit:, Enroll - This is a benefit that the employee has selected to enroll in., , Keep/Update - This is an existing benefit that will be kept with, or, without changes., , Cancel - This is a benefit that will be dropped for the current, enrollment period.

Provides a method for selecting benefit elections based on the bargaining unit , of an employee's primary position.  Employees must be in one of these , bargaining units in order to be included in this filter set.
Provides a method to select benefit elections based on the benefit/deduction , code. Employees' benefit elections must be for one of these benefits in order , to be included in this filter set.

Provides a method for selecting benefit elections based on the department of an , employees primary position.  Employees must be in one of these departments in , order to be included in this filter set.

This field describes the resulting selection made by this filter. This, text and the key are the only information displayed on a resolution, form or on forms where this filter is used. Therefore, users rely on, this description to make the correct selection.

Provides a method to select benefit elections by the current status, assigned to the election.  (The history of statuses for a benefit, election are stored in reverse chronological order, so the current, status is always at the top.)

Provides a method for selecting benefit elections based on the employment , status of an employee's primary position.  Employees must have one of these , employment statuses in order to be included in this filter set.

Provides a method for using a saved list to select benefit elections for , particular employees.  This is the name of a saved list containing the employee , IDs that can be included in this filter set.

Provides a method to select benefit elections by the benefit/deductions , institution type (the institution type on the BEND form).  Employees' benefit , elections must be for one of these institution types in order to be included in , this filter set.

Provides a method for HR staff to filter on employees whose last names begin , with a particular letter of the alphabet.  This is a list of letters of the , alphabet.  Employees must have a last name starting with one of these letters , in order to be included in this filter set.
Provides a method for selecting benefit elections based on the location of an , employees primary position.  Employees must be in one of these locations in , order to be included in this filter set.
Provides a method for selecting benefit elections based on the pay cycle of an , employees primary position.  Employees must have one of these pay cycles in , order to be included in this filter set.

Provides a method for selecting benefit elections based on the position type of , an employee's primary position.  Employees must be in one of these position , types in order to be included in this filter set.

System-maintained field to store the source of the benefit election, signature, either Employee-signed or System-signed.  Elections can be, and, usually are, signed by employees during an open enrollment period.  However, , when an enrollment period is closed out, the system will record a "System" , signature , for employees who were eligible to elect benefits during that enrollment period , but, who either didn't participate in the online enrollment process at all, or who , made online, elections but did not sign their elections.
This date is reserved for future use.  For example, it could possibly, be used to indicate when the employee's benefit elections which were, made online were verified and completed.

If employees should be provided with the option to opt out of the, benefits within a specific benefit type, enter Yes in this field. Use this field to specify a date on which benefits will become, effective.  Benefits which become active after this effective date will, also be included and handled properly in Benefit Enrollment.  Any, benefits specified in the plan package must have a benefit cost record, for the effective date or the benefit cannot be calculated unless the, benefit and its cost record do not become active until after the, effective date.  Benefits without a benefit cost record as of the, effective date will not be displayed in Benefit Enrollment unless the, benefit's effective date and its cost record effective date match and, are after the effective date.

COMPUTED.COLUMN.CODE: string[] xlResult1; , key xlKeyPospay for file Pospay;, xlKeyPospay = vlHrasofPpwgPospayId; xlResult1 = vlPospaySalaryMax;, return (money)xlResult1;
ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: HRASOFPOS
PURPOSE: To identify the maximum salary at which the position can, be filled.  The maximum salary can be derived from the, current fiscal year salary table based upon the maximum, grade and step entered by the user.  If this is the case,, the user should not be able to alter the salary amount., If no maximum grade or step is entered, then the user can, directly enter a maximum salary amount in the field.  If, this is the case, the maximum step and salary fields, should be disabled for data entry., Only if the maximum salary field is null can the user, enter data in the maximum grade and step fields.

COMPUTED.COLUMN.CODE: string[] xlResult1; , key xlKeyPospay for file Pospay;, xlKeyPospay = vlHrasofPpwgPospayId; xlResult1 = vlPospaySalaryMid;, return (money)xlResult1;
ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: HRASOFPOS
PURPOSE: To identify the min-point salary for the position.  The, mid-point salary can be derived from the current fiscal, year salary table based upon the mid-point tier, grade and, step entered by the user.  If this is the case, the user, should not be able to alter the salary amount., , If no mid-point tier, grade or step is entered, then the, used can directly enter a mid-point salary amount in the, field.  If this is the case, the mid-point tier, grade,, and step fields should be disabled for data entry., , Only if the mid-point salary field is null can the user, enter data in the mid-point tier, grade and step fields.

Description of box codes

Field can contain limited selectioin of values.  Its, content is validated against the MAG.MEDIA.FOOTNOTES valcd, table.  It is a 2 digit field with leading zeros.  For, certain tax forms, some information which is printed in, the footnote section of the paper tax form must appear in, specific fields on magnetic media used to report the form, to Revenue Canada.  However, there is no specific footnot, number assigned to the info so there is no way to determin, what information is to be placed on the mag media., Will provide link between footnote and mag media., This field will accept data for other tax forms, but it is, currently used only for T4 processing.  When this field, contains a value, the BXC.MAG.MEDIA.ONLY field must be "Y"
To be able to track footnote codes for T4 Box Codes

Description of the disability.

The target database definition identifies important technical, information about the database to which the data mart is being written., It tells Envision where the data base is located and how to communicate, with it.  The default designation can be changed at run-time.  The, database to which the Benefits Enrollment data mart will most often be, written should be specified here.
This parameter will be used to determine which e-mail address to, include in the data mart for each employee.

This flag is used to toggle the inclusion of employees with no benefits, in the data mart.  If employees with no benefits are not included in, the data mart, then reports cannot give any indication as to how many, employees have no benefits because the data simply is not there.  By, including these employees in the data mart, more meaningful reports can, be generated.
This hierarchy is used to determine what name and address will be, included in the HR data marts.

This code will be used in the Benefits Enrollment data mart for any, employee who has no benefits during a given month.  Enabling the use of, a benefit code that does not exist in the Colleage database will allow, those employees to be included in the data mart for more accurate head, counts of employee benefit trends.

This description will be used in the Benefits Enrollment data mart for, any employee who has no benefits during a given month.  Enabling the, use of a benefit code and description that does not exist in the, Colleage database will allow those employees to be included in the data, mart for more accurate head counts of employee benefit trends.
This flag is used to allow the client flexibility in using either base, HR data or the Resource Database to determine each employee's primary, position and supervisor.

This in-use flag helps ensure that employees' seniority plan records are, secured from accidental modification. An employee's seniority plan is, considered in use, and is therefore protected, as soon as the employee, is enrolled in the seniority plan., , As long as this parameter is set to "Yes," the user cannot modify, certain data in employees' seniority plan records unless the user has, been given the appropriate security class. An error message is , displayed if any attempt is made to modify protected data., , If you set this parameter to "No," security is turned off and all, users are allowed to modify employees' seniority plan records. When , a user accesses certain screens having to do with an employee's , seniority plans,such as the Person's Seniority Plan screen, , the message "In Use Override by Parameter" is displayed at the bottom , of the screen. This serves to warn users that they have the ability , to change things that otherwise might be protected. The user , must press ~RETURN~ to acknowledge this warning and proceed., , Note: You may wish to set this parameter to "No" during initial, setup of the Personnel module to ease data entry. During regular day-, to-day operation, however, it is advisable to keep this parameter set, to "Yes" and to provide the ability to change protected information, via the user's security class.

To define the value that represents "100% load" so that, the percentage of the actual load may be calculated and, stored in PPWG.WORKLOAD.PCT.
Description of the Load Definition

A load definition defines the levels of faculty workload.  There is, a minimum load, a maximum load, an overload maximum and an intended, load., The load definition is, in essence, the range between the minimum, load and the maximum load.  If a person is assigned a load that, is greater than the maximum load, they are considered to be in an, overload situation.  The overload maximum is the greates allowable, load., The intended load is the desired load level.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: ACCURAL.RATES
PURPOSE: Maximum number of hours that can be rolled over into another leave, plan if this leave plan is eligible to roll leave., , Certain leave types are allowed to roll unused leave from one leave, plan to another. At the beginning of a plan year, when the leave, carryover calculation is processed, the number of hours in excess of, the carryover limit, if any, can be moved into another leave type., For example, an employee may be allowed carryover 240 hours of, vacation from one year to the next. If the employee has more than, 240 hours of accrued vacation at the beginning of the plan year, the, institution may allow the employee to roll the excess of 240 hours, into a sick leave plan rather than lose the excess. The maximum, rollover allows you to control how many hours the employee can roll, into the sick leave plan. The rollover maximum may be incremental, based on the number of service years or the same for all service, years., , There are three options for maximum rollover. They are:,   Null entry means all hours in excess of carryover limit will be,   rolled., ,   Zero entry means that no hours in excess of carryover limit will be,   rolled., ,   A positive number means that no more than the entered amount of,   hours in excess of the carryover limit will be rolled., , Negative numbers are not allowed.

But this flag, provides for an override on the employee and benefit/deduction level., Because the CDD element was released on an early software update, (Change Request 22703.11 and RP 1267) and the design changed after that, S/U was released, the name is a little backwards.  Setting this flag to, "Y" makes an employee ben/ded combination INELIGIBLE for arrears., Because this field is intended as an override for default behavior, the, value that would be equivalent to the default behavior cannot be, entered. Valid values for this flag are "Y" or null.

The total value of the assignment contract for the load period., This field is calculated if not overridden by the user.  , , For hourly (HRLY) type payment contracts, this field is zero (value , cannot be derived until actual hours are worked) unless the user has, overridden the value., , For fixed payment by assignment (FPA) type payment contracts,, the load period total value is recalculated each time is is displayed, to equal the sum of the associated assignment's base amount., , For salaried type payment contracts (SLRY, SDI, SDA), the load period, total value is recalculated only if it is null.  The salaried, wage as of the start date of the load period is summarized for all, position and the total load period value is derived.  Once set for, salaried type contracts, the value is never recalculated but can be, overridden by the user.

This is the code used to determine which type of assignment this, record is.  Depending on the assignment type, this record points, to a different set of records in the Student Systems application., Asgmt Types "S" are course section assignments (instructional load), Asgmt Types "V" are campus org advisors (non-instructional #1 load), Asgmt Types "M" are campus org members (non-instructional #2 load)

If the Position Control module is used at your institution, the, maximum grade, step, and group can be used to derive a position's, maximum salary or wage from the specified salary/wage table. The same, amount may be entered for the minimum, midpoint, and maximum if there, is only one salary or wage for the position., .D, Displays the maximum salary/wage at which this position can be filled., .D

To identify the mid-point salary for the position.  The, mid-point salary can be derived from the current fiscal, year salary table based upon the mid-point tier, grade and, step entered by the user.  If this is the case, the user, should not be able to alter the salary amount., , If no mid-point tier, grade or step is entered, then the, user can directly enter a mid-point salary amount in the, field.  If this is the case, the mid-point tier, grade,, and step fields should be disabled for data entry., , Only if the mid-point salary field is null can the user, enter data in the mid-point tier, grade and step fields.

To identify the minimum salary at which the position can, be filled.  The minimum salary can be derived from the, current fiscal year salary table based upon the minimum, grade and step entered by the user.  If this is the case,, the user should not be able to alter the salary amount., , If no minimum grade or step is entered, then the used can, directly enter a minimum salary amount in the field.  If, this is the case, the minimum step and salary fields, should be disabled for data entry., , Only if the minimum salary field is null can the user, enter data in the minimum grade and step fields.

To associate a salary table to the position.  This field, is only applicable if Position Control is being used., Otherwise, Personnel has no access to the salary tables., , Need lookup on Position Control salary table.

This is the counterpart to POSPAY.SALARY.MIN. It is, required because hourly wages are 4 decimal and salaries, are two decimals.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: PPDTWORK

It will, be multiplied by the number of differential work time, units and added to the earnings.  If the earnings differ-, ential was entered as a dollar amount, that amount is, defaulted here.  If the earnings differential code is a, percentage, the percentage is multiplied by the hourly, rate for the position and the resulting dollar amount, defaults to this position., This cannot be modified by the user.

ELEMENT.ASSOC.NAME: PPDTWORK

It is computed by multiplying, PPDT.EARN.FACTOR.RATES by the salary amount for this line, item, or by the hourly rate times the number of work time, units.  It the earning's type indicates that the differen-, tial amount is to be included in the calculation, the, PPDT.EARN.DIFF.AMTS must be added to the salary amount or, the computed hours times rate amount before the factor is, applied.

If the flag is, H, the amount in this field is the number of work time, units multiplied by the hourly rate in PPDT.HOURLY.RATES., If the flag is S, this amount is the value in, PPDT.SALARY.RATES. This is a logical view of the PAYCNTRL. It is a permanent, key file that stores the period date and pay cycle of the, payroll currently being run. The record ID is PAYROLL.PROCESSING., The record is first updated with the period date and pay cycle at the, beginning of the payroll calculation process. It remains populated, with the current period date and pay cycle until one of three things, happens:, , 1. If the payroll calculation fails to run satisfactorily., 2. The user goes back into one of the payroll preparation steps after, running the payroll calculation., 3. The current payroll is processed to completion, thru the Employee, History Update.

This field displays the adjusted start date when the person begins, to accumulate seniority hours (versus eligibility hours) in this plan., , During Seniority Processing, the adjusted start date will always be , used to determine if the hours under consideration are accumulated , into the person's seniority hour totals or the person's eligibility, hour totals., , Normally, this date is set automatically by the system during the , seniority calculation process when the person's work hours have , accrued enough eligibility to qualify the person to begin to , accumulate seniority hours.  The seniority start date and this , adjusted seniority start date are set equal to the work date when the, person's hours crossed the eligibilty hour requirements defined in the, Seniority Plan., , Clients can set this adjusted seniority start date to force the , seniority calculations to begin accumulation of seniority hours as of, a specified date, even though the eligibility hour requirements had not, been met.

The computed number of work hours completed by the employee which , count towards the eligibility limit of this seniority plan as of , the last computed date, PSP.AS.OF.DATE.  , Limit range of  0 - 146,000.00 (8 hours per day for 50 years).

This is the last date on which any work performed will be, applied to this plan for this employee. This date can be set, by the TERM screen, or by a manual process. If this date is set,, no work performed by the employee after this date will be applied, to this plan.

The date this seniority information for this employee expires.  , This date can be set by hand or by the calculation process.  Most , often this date will be set by the calculation process if it is a , date of concern to the plan.  , , For example, some plans say that if no work is performed under , this plan for 6 months, the seniority balance should go to 0.  , This date would be set to the date 6 months in the future by , the calculation process.

The purpose of this field is to insure that only one batch is    , exported at any given time.  When a batch is exported using screen    , RCXP, this field is set to the ELF Batch ID of the batch, being exported.  Once this field has a value in it, no other batch    , may be exported.    , When an import is run (RCHU) for the previously exported batch, this  , field is reset to null.  , The Batch ID is needed so that we can get the record in, ELF.BATCH and then to ELF.TRANSACTIONS to ensure that records, have actually been exported.  If no records have been exported,, this field is set to null so that another batch may be exported.

The purpose of this field is to store the OS filename of the, exported batch of ROEs.  The default name of the file is set-up, on ELFT.  When exporting a batch from RCXP, a user may detail to, ELFT and change the filename for that one batch - this is the name, we will store., When an import is run (RCHU), we display this filename rather than, making the user remember the name of the file they exported.  When, an import is run for the previously exported batch, this field, is reset to null.

Sequential key to SENIORITY.DTL interim file.  Use S.NEXT.KEY to, generate a new key., , The information on this file is obtained from the PR.TIME.HISTORY file.,  A batch process will select all payroll time history records which , have not been processed by the seniority process and convert them , into detail records for each seniority plan.  , , All fields on this record will be single valued (except for comments)., At some point, the information on this file must be summarized , and then purged to reduce the size of the file.  The detail records , on this file should be considered an interim step.  , , Their purpose is to provide data for calculation processes , to produce the final PER.SENIORITY.PLAN and PERSPDTL file records.  , Once those  records are produced, these detail records can be  , purged.  These detail records will also aid in troubleshooting , the custom calculation processes.  , , The key to this file is a sequential number.  The seniority stamp , flag will indicates whether or not the calculation process for , this plan has processed this record.  The calculation process sets , this flag. , , Two types of records will exist on this file.  , , One record will be the detail record containing detailed work , information on a daily basis, , The second record type will be an adjustment record.  The , adjustment record will be used to update the PSP.SENIORITY.HOURS , field or the PSP.ELIGIBILITY.HOURS field in the PER.SENIORITY.PLAN , record.  An adjustment screen will allow users to enter an amount , to increment or decrement these fields.  The adjustment screen , will create an adjustment record on the SENIORITY.DTL file , as a tracking mechanism.

Description of seniority plan template

You may include any seniority plan in the seniority plan template,, regardless of the date range of the seniority plan. This makes, it possible for you to include seniority plans that have been, defined for future use. When you enroll someone using the template,, the start and end dates of the seniority plans included in the, template are analyzed and the person is enrolled only in those that, are effective as of, or after, the enrollment date.

It contans each 9-month full-Time faculty minimum salary for total eleven , hightest education levels.  The 9-month, full-time curriculum faculty member , shall not earn less than the minimum salary that provided by the General , Assembly for his/her education level, regardless of whether their degree is , applicable to what they are teaching.

The minimum salaries for community college 9-month full-time faculty faculty , member is based upon the following eleven educational levels:, 01. Less than High School, 02. High School or Equivalent, 03. One Year of College, 04. Vocational Diploma, 05. Two Years of College, 06. Associate Degree, 07. Three/Four Years College, 08. Bachelor's Degree, 09. Master's Degree, 10. Doctor's Degree, 11. Educational Specialist
This is the key for each educational level. Total eleven minimum salaries for , community , college faculty are based upon total eleven educational levels.

It contains the monthly 9-month full-Time faculty minimum salary, which is , associated with each education level. There are total eleven education levels.  , Each monthly minimum salary will be divided by 9 automatically by the system , after the 9-month's minimum salary is entered by the collegue.
